      <abstract>
        <p>Howard Goldberg reviews Pierre Boniface's 2006 Apremonte wine (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>If the breath of spring could be bottled as a dry wine, it might resemble Pierre Boniface's 2006 Apremont, a low-alcohol Alpine white from Savoie in eastern France.</p>
        <p>Light, aromatic and as citric as a just-picked grapefruit, Apremont is made from a rarely encountered grape, the Jacquère. Chill it lightly. Successive vintages could easily become perennial favorites.</p>
      </block>
